  <section class="sec">
    <p class="sl">Local knowledge</p>
    <h2>Plumpton — Established Outer West, 1980s–1990s Brick Homes, Cold Keilor Plateau Winters</h2>
    <div class="local-box"><p>Plumpton is a well-established outer western suburb sitting on the Keilor Plateau, developed primarily through the 1980s and 1990s as the suburban fringe extended west of Keilor Downs. The housing stock is predominantly solid brick veneer homes from that era — a significant proportion fitted with either open fireplaces or early-generation slow-combustion wood heaters as part of the original build. Many of these systems have had limited professional maintenance over the decades, with creosote and soot accumulating through regular winter use. The Keilor Plateau sits elevated above the western plains, and Plumpton experiences noticeably colder winters than inner Melbourne — cold north-westerly winds sweep across the plateau from June through August, and overnight temperatures frequently drop below four degrees. Homes here typically run wood fires from mid-April through to October. The suburb borders Keilor Downs, Sydenham and Caroline Springs, and we cover Plumpton as part of our regular Keilor corridor run. We are familiar with the brick veneer chimney configurations common in homes built through the late 1980s and the style of slow-combustion flue systems installed in that period.</p></div>
  </section>

